          <p class="text-gray-700">Webflow is visual, WordPress is code-first (mostly). Webflow: cleaner sites, faster builds, no plugins. WordPress: more plugins, cheaper hosting, larger ecosystem. Webflow for designers. WordPress for content-heavy sites with plugin needs.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-2 border-gray-200 p-6 rounded-lg">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Can clients edit Webflow sites?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700">Technically: yes. Practically: no. Webflow has Editor mode, but it's still complex. Most clients email for changes instead. If client editing is critical, consider Squarespace or WordPress. Webflow is better for agencies who maintain sites long-term.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-2 border-gray-200 p-6 rounded-lg">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">What happens if I export code?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700">You get clean HTML/CSS/JS. Host anywhere, customize further. But: you lose Webflow's visual editor. Updates happen in code, not Webflow. Export once = great. Export repeatedly = painful. Choose this path only if you have development skills.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-2 border-gray-200 p-6 rounded-lg">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Is Webflow good for e-commerce?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700">It's capable but expensive. Webflow E-commerce starts at $42/mo plus 2% transaction fees. For simple stores (under 100 products), it's excellent design-wise. For complex stores, WooCommerce (WordPress/10Web) is more cost-effective.</p>
